<b>Bondy's theorem</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../977/30977.xml">
theorem</link> in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../537/387537.xml">
computational learning theory</link> that appear in a 1972 article by <link>
Adrian Bondy</link>. The theorem is as follows:<p>

Let <it>C</it> be a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../075/3326075.xml">
concept class</link> over a finite domain <it>X</it>. Then there exists a subset <it>S</it> of <it>X</it> with the size at most |<it>C</it>| &amp;minus; 1 such that <it>S</it> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../019/3326019.xml">
witness set</link> for every concept in <it>C</it>. </p>
<p>

This implies that every finite concept class <it>C</it> has its <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../018/3326018.xml">
teaching dimension</link> bounded by |<it>C</it>| &amp;minus; 1.</p>


